CodeSentry

Token-Efficient Source Code Security Scanner
Approach to Vulnerability Detection

 
Scan  ·  Score  ·  Enrich  ·  Report — in one self-contained pipeline

1. Overview
CodeSentry is a source code security scanner built around a simple principle: use deterministic, open-source tools to do the heavy lifting, and reserve large language model (LLM) calls for the narrow set of tasks where they add real value — triage, explanation, and narrative enrichment. This keeps scan cost predictable and avoids sending raw source code to any LLM.
The system runs as an eight-stage automated pipeline, taking a project from raw upload (ZIP, local directory, or Git URL) through scanning, normalization, deterministic risk scoring, optional LLM enrichment, and a self-contained HTML report.
#
Stage
What happens
1
Ingest
Accepts a ZIP upload, local directory, or Git URL (https only, shallow clone).
2
Scan
Runs Semgrep, Gitleaks, Trivy, and OSV-Scanner independently.
3
Normalize
Maps every scanner's output into one common Finding schema, with CWE → OWASP Top 10 mapping.
4
Dedup
Merges identical findings (same rule, file, and line) and counts occurrences.
5
Risk Score
Computes a deterministic 0–100 score using exponential saturation.
6
Enrich
Optional LLM pass adds plain-language narrative to pre-filtered findings only.
7
Render
Produces a single self-contained HTML report (no external calls).
8
Persist
Saves scan metadata and findings to SQLite or PostgreSQL for audit history.
 

2. Safe Ingestion
Before any scanning begins, CodeSentry applies a set of guardrails to the input source so that untrusted code cannot compromise the scanning host itself:
• ZIP upload, local directory, or Git URL as input sources (CLI or REST API).
• Git cloning restricted to https:// only, with --depth 1 shallow clone.
• Path-traversal protection: rejects absolute paths, drive letters, and ".." segments.
• Zip-bomb guard via a compression-ratio cap, plus per-file, total-extracted, and file-count size limits.
• Executable and binary file extensions are blocked from ever reaching disk.
• Noise directories are skipped automatically (.git, node_modules, venv, dist).
• Upload validation covers file extension, non-empty content, and maximum size.
3. Pluggable Security Scanners
Each scanner runs independently, can be toggled on or off, and executes under a hard timeout with shell=False subprocess calls — no shell injection surface, no runaway processes.
Scanner
Purpose
Semgrep
Static Application Security Testing (SAST) — code-level vulnerability rules (SQL injection, XSS, command injection, etc.).
Gitleaks
Hardcoded secret and credential detection across code and history.
Trivy
Dependency vulnerabilities plus container and Infrastructure-as-Code (IaC) misconfigurations.
OSV-Scanner
Open-source dependency vulnerability database lookups (known CVEs).
 
All four tools are auto-detected from the project's tools/ folder, so no manual PATH configuration is required.
4. Normalization & Deterministic Risk Scoring
Normalization
• All scanner output is mapped into one common Finding schema.
• CWE identifiers are mapped to OWASP Top 10 (2021) categories, A01–A10.
• Severity, confidence, CVSS score, fixed-version data, and a snippet of 10 lines or fewer are extracted per finding.
• Secrets are masked everywhere — raw values are never stored.
• Identical findings (same rule, file, and line) are deduplicated and counted.
Risk Scoring
Risk is scored 0–100 using exponential saturation, so a single Critical finding dominates the score even against a large pile of Low-severity findings:
• A single Critical finding floors the project score at 70.
• A single High finding floors the project score at 50.
• Per-finding score = severity base × CVSS boost, discounted by scanner confidence (High/Medium/Low).
• Project score is a severity-weighted aggregation across all findings, and is designed to never quite reach 100.
5. Optional LLM Enrichment
The LLM never sees raw source code — only normalized findings with snippets of 10 lines or fewer. This is the core of the token-efficiency design:
• Fix templates first: common vulnerability classes (SQLi, XSS, command injection, path traversal, hardcoded secrets, weak crypto, insecure deserialization, XXE) get free, zero-token deterministic guidance before any LLM call is made.
• Grouping & batching: duplicate findings collapse to one representative plus a count; batching caps put a hard ceiling on LLM cost per scan.
• Response caching: a disk cache keyed by finding ID and model means re-scans cost nothing.
• Provider-agnostic: works with any OpenAI-compatible API (OpenAI, Azure OpenAI, Ollama, LM Studio, vLLM). Setting LLM_PROVIDER=none runs the pipeline fully offline.
6. Reporting
CodeSentry produces a single, self-contained HTML report: no CDN dependencies, no external network requests, and Jinja2 autoescaping so that scanned code cannot inject script into its own report. The report includes:
• Title, project name, scan date/time, and detected technology stack
• Executive summary with overall risk score and level badge
• Severity stat tiles and a bar chart
• OWASP Top 10 (2021) mapping chart
• Sortable vulnerability table with per-finding detail, grouped by file
• Dependency vulnerabilities with fixed versions
• Secret findings, with values always masked
• Container / IaC misconfigurations
• A prioritized action plan and false-positive review notes
• Appendix with per-scanner status and duration
The report supports light and dark mode, is fully self-contained, and phones home to nothing.
7. Interfaces, Background Jobs & Persistence
Component
Details
CLI
python cli.py path/to/project or python cli.py project.zip --output report.html — prints risk score, severity counts, and report path.
REST API (FastAPI)
GET /health · POST /scans/upload · POST /scans/path · GET /scans/{id} · GET /scans/{id}/report.
Background Jobs (Celery)
CELERY_TASK_ALWAYS_EAGER=true runs inline for development; set to false with a worker for async processing via Redis.
Persistence (SQLAlchemy)
Scan table stores status, risk score/level, and stats JSON; FindingRecord stores per-scan findings for audit, on SQLite or PostgreSQL.
 

8. Security-First Design Principles
• Scanned code is never executed — static analysis only.
• Subprocess calls use argument lists only, with resolved executables and hard timeouts (no shell=True).
• Secrets are masked everywhere: in findings, snippets, and database records.
• Scanner-reported file paths are re-sanitized before rendering into the report.
• Git cloning is restricted to https:// with --depth 1.
• Jinja2 autoescaping ensures scanned code cannot inject script into the generated report.
9. Summary
CodeSentry's approach can be summarized as deterministic-first, LLM-second: every finding is discovered, normalized, deduplicated, and scored using open-source scanners and rule-based logic. The LLM is an optional layer used only to explain and prioritize findings that have already been identified deterministically — never to find vulnerabilities on its own, and never with access to raw source code. The result is a config-driven (.env), pluggable, auditable pipeline that produces a prioritized, self-contained security report at predictable and minimal token cost.